# {{domain_id}}

> Generated by `hnsx new` from the `{{template}}` template.
>
> **Edit `domain.yaml` to change the harness.** This README stays short on
> purpose — it points you at the next command, not at long-form docs.

## What you have

```
{{domain_id}}/
├── domain.yaml    ← the Harness: agents, prompts, skills, tools, policies
├── README.md      ← this file
└── .gitignore     ← secrets, eval cache, runtime artifacts
```

## Variables used by this template

| Variable | Default | What it controls |
|---|---|---|
| `domain_id` | `{{domain_id}}` | The Domain id (also the directory name). |
| `company_name` | `Acme` | Branding in prompts and tool descriptions. |
| `template` | `{{template}}` | Which built-in template was rendered. |

Override at generation time:

```bash
hnsx new {{domain_id}} --template {{template}} --set company_name="Globex"
```

## Validate locally

```bash
hnsx validate domain.yaml
```

This checks the YAML against the DomainSpec schema and surfaces any
typos before you try to run it.

## Run locally (no server)

```bash
hnsx run --domain domain.yaml --trigger '{"question":"hi"}'
```

`hnsx run` boots the embedded Python worker against the local
DomainSpec — useful for fast iteration without standing up Postgres +
Server + Worker.

## Register against a running HnsX server

```bash
# Start the local stack if it isn't already
hnsx up

# Push this Domain into the registry
hnsx domain apply --file domain.yaml

# Trigger a Session
hnsx session trigger --domain {{domain_id}} --question "hi"

# Tail the observation stream
hnsx session tail <session-id>
```

## Run an Eval

If the template ships with an EvalSet, you can verify the Harness
behaves as expected with:

```bash
hnsx eval set list
hnsx eval run start <eval-set-id> --domain {{domain_id}}
```

